I"Ä*<h1 id="deep-learning-with-pytorch-step-by-step">Deep Learning with PyTorch Step-by-Step</h1>

<p>Most modern neural networks are trained using maximum likelihood. This means that the cost function is simply the negative log-likelihood, equivalently described as the cross-entropy between the training data and the model distribution. This cost function is given by
 [J(Î¸) = \log p_{model}(y | x)]
The specific form of the cost function changes from model to model, depending on the specific form of \(\log p_{model}\) The expansion of the above equation typically yields some terms that do not depend on the model parameters and may be discarded. For example, if \(pmodel(y | x) = N(y; f(x; Î¸), I)\),then we recover the mean squared error cost,
[$$$</p>

<p>In this blog, we will:</p>

<p>â€¢ define a simple linear regression model</p>

<p>â€¢ walk through every step of gradient descent: initializing parameters,
performing a forward pass, computing errors and loss, computing gradients, and updating parameters</p>

<p>â€¢ understand gradients using equations, code, and geometry</p>

<p>â€¢ understand the difference between batch, mini-batch, and stochastic gradient descent</p>

<p>â€¢ visualize the effects on the loss of using different learning rates</p>

<p>â€¢ understand the importance of standardizing / scaling features</p>

